guage and Co-Speech Gesture -- tChapter 13. Words, gestures, and beyond: Forms of multimodal metaphor in the use of spoken language -- tChapter 14. Metonymy first, metaphor second: A cognitivesemiotic approach to multimodal figures of thought in co-speech gesture -- tVI. Metaphor Involving Music and Sound -- tChapter 15. Music, language, and multimodal metaphor -- tChapter 16. The role of non-verbal sound and music in multimodal metaphor -- tVII. Metaphor and Film -- tChapter 17. Multimodal metaphor in classical film theory from the 1920s to the 1950s -- tChapter 18. Multimodal expressions of the HUMAN VICTIM IS ANIMAL metaphor in horror films -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Metaphor studies" has over the past 30 years become a discipline in its own right, mainly because of the cognitive linguistic claim that metaphors characterize thought, not just language. But most metaphor scholars hitherto focus exclusively on its purely verbal expressions. Since both persuasive and narrative discourses in contemporary society increasingly draw on modalities other than language alone, sustained research into a broader range of manifestations of metaphor is imperative. This volume is the first book-length study to investigate multimodal occurrences of metaphor, and is of interest to scholars interested in metaphor as well as in multimodal discourse. Each chapter investigates metaphors whose identification and interpretation depend on the co-presence of at least two of the following modalities: language, visuals, gestures, sound, music. On the basis of case studies in a variety of discourse genres (advertising, cartoons, films, comics, conversation, music, amply represented in photographs, logos, drawings, film stills, and musical scores), the contributors demonstrate that, and how, metaphor can occur multimodally, providing ideas and methodological angles enabling further theorizing and testing in this rapidly expanding field. Covering creative as well as conceptual metaphors, and where appropriate evaluating cultural factors governing metaphor interpretation, the contributors provide a wealth of material for studying the conceptual and rhetorical force of metaphor in contemporary society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMetaphor. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aPragmatik. 4aVisuelle Kommunikation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive linguistics.  apragmatics.  avisual communication.1 aCaballero, Rosario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCienki, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEerden, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEggertsson, Gunnar Theodór, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForceville, Charles J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForceville, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoller, Veronika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaes, Alfons, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatsunaka, Yoshihiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMittelberg, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRefaie, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohdin, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchilperoord, Joost, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShinohara, Kazuko, econtributor.4ctb4https: